clinical_study.brief_title: Safety of Subcutaneous Testosterone Enanthate in Adult Male Hypogonadism
clinical_study.official_title: An Open-Label Study to Evaluate the Safety of Testosterone Enanthate After Two Single-Dose Injections Via QuickShot® Testosterone by Intended Users and QuickShot™ Summative Usability Study

brief_summary.textblock: Evaluation of the safety and tolerability of testosterone enanthate (TE) following a single dose via QuickShot® Testosterone (QST) when administered by intended users in a usability study.

detailed_description.textblock: Intended users are patients as well as patient caregivers, such as family members or friends who are able to assist the patient to administer the medication (i.e. lay users). One user group of approximately 15 patients will have their dose administered by a qualified healthcare professional (HCP).

primary_outcome.measure: Number of Patients With Adverse Events Receiving Testosterone Enanthate Via QST Auto-injector.
primary_outcome.description: Intended users were patients experiencing an adverse event that was considered to be a TEAE if the adverse event started on or after randomization, or existed prior to randomization and worsened in severity or relatedness to QST (QuickShot® Testosterone auto-injector) after randomization.

arm_group.description: Testosterone enanthate administered subcutaneously once each week. Auto-injection of QST 50 mg or 75 mg or 100 mg [Device: QuickShot® Testosterone (QST)]

intervention.description: SC injections of QST 50 mg or 75 mg or 100 mg

participant_flow.recruitment_details: In total, 66 patients were enrolled, of which 65 patients were randomized and were included in the Safety Population.
participant_flow.pre_assignment_details: The Safety Population included all patients who were randomized and took at least one dose of Investigational Product. The Safety Population was used as the denominator in percentage calculations.
